ce:section.ce:para:
A combination of microwave and thermal methods was used to synthesize GQDs (

                              Scheme 1
                           ). Specifically, citric acid (5 g) was added to 5 mL deionized water gradually. The resulting solution was placed in a Teflon kettle and put into a microwave oven at 150 W for 8 min, then heated at 180 °C. Finally, the transparent solution turned into a viscous brown liquid and GQD was formed. The synthesized matter was cooled at ambient temperature. To eliminate the insoluble carbon product and small unfused molecules, the viscous liquid was filtered through a microporous membrane [59–61] (
                              Scheme 1
                           ).

By some modification, ZIF-8 was synthesized according to the previous procedure. The methanolic solution of 2-Methly imidazole (1.268 g in 50 mL of methanol as solvent), drop by drop, was added into the methanolic solution of Zn (NO3)2-6 H2O (0.735 g in 50 mL of methanol), under stirring at room temperature. The obtained mixture was stirred, then rested for 24 h. The resulting precipitate was collected by centrifugation, afterward washed three times by pure methanol, finally dried at 60 °C for 8 h [36] (
                              Scheme 1
                           ).

Zinc nitrate hexahydrate (0.735 g), polyvinylpyrrolidone (PVP) (0.5 g), and 1 mL of the GQDs in MeOH (2, 4, 8, 10, 15, 20%Wt of GQD based on weight of pure ZIF-8 final yield) were gradually added to (50 mL) methanol, then sonicated for 15 mins. In the next stage, progressively 2-Methyl imidazole (1.268 g in 50 mL of methanol) was added to the previous solution. With a slight difference, other steps were as before. To achieve the final drying, the prepared nanocomposite was heated at 80 °C for 10 h [36,62] (
                              Scheme 1
                           ).
